{"cursor":"12568","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn economics, 'profit maximization' is the short run or long run process by\nwhich a firm determines the price and output level that returns the greatest\nprofit. There are several approaches to this problem. The total\nrevenue–total cost perspective relies on the fact that profit equals\nrevenue minus cost and focuses on maximizing this difference, and the marginal\nrevenue–marginal cost perspective is based on the fact that total profit\nreaches its maximum point where marginal revenue equals marginal cost.\n","linknr":193,"url":"Profit_maximization","recorded":1362684307,"links":22,"instances":["economics","economics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Profit","Pricing"],"headings":["Basic definitions","Total revenue - total cost perspective","Marginal revenue-marginal cost perspective","Case in which maximizing revenue is equivalent","Changes in total costs and profit maximization","Markup pricing","Marginal product of labor, marginal revenue product of labor, and profit maximization","See also","Notes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d5/Profit_max_total_small.svg/250px-Profit_max_total_small.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Profit_max_marginal_small.svg/250px-Profit_max_marginal_small.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/d/1/4d14b79d8fd02dee764bb84abba239d5.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["output","economics"],["profit","economics"]],"members":["profit","outp